message:
Added css3 selectors conforming to w3c specification and test cases. The
selectors are not entirely done yet:
* namespaces are not handled yet.

Anything that does not contain namespaces is expected to work correctly.

Two types of w3c tests are skipped:
* those with namespaces,
* those that crashes less.js.

W3c specification: http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-selectors/
W3c test cases: http://www.w3.org/Style/CSS/Test/CSS3/Selectors/current/
Linked comments handling documentation in readme.
Added new test case for variables.

Less language supports four arithmetical operations plus '+', minus '-',
multiplication '*', division '/' and parentheses '(' ')'. Operations are
evaluated in usual order:

* parentheses are evaluated first,
* multiplication/division takes precedence over addition and subtraction,
* non commutative operations are evaluated from left to right.

Only operations on numbers are supported. Operations on strings,
identifiers or anything else are not.

On Units:
Numbers in CSS can have specified units: "21px 14cm 4.56%'. Less does not
convert between different units, it takes numbers as they are. The result
of mathematical operation is assigned leftmost explicitly stated unit
type.

Empty Separator vs Whitespaces in Expressions:
Less4j follows current less.js behavior. More on the topic is on wiki
https://github.com/SomMeri/less4j/wiki/Supported-Less-Language .

Expression are Occasionally Ignored:
Expressions are not evaluated inside font declarations and
xxxxx-aspect-ratio media features. It is because those things allow ratio
"number/number" as a valid parameter and expression evaluation would make
them impossible to use.
[ci skip] Documenting: added description to pom.xml and updated readme.

First draft of mixins including unit tests. It forced me to implement also
lazy loading of variables and last declaration win strategy for them.

What is done:
* pure mixins with or without parameters - they must have () (`.mixin() {declaration: value; }`).

What is NOT yet done:
* rulesets that doubles as mixins - this is not treated as mixin `.notMixin { declaration: value; }`,
* guarded mixins,
* error/warning on faulty default values,
* patterns matching.
